17 May 2011
Libya's oil minister 'defects'
17 May 2011
Libyan oil minister defects
17 May 2011
Libya: arrest warrants sought for Gaddafi family
16 May 2011
In the multilateral age in which we live, it is virtually impossible for any country – with the possible exception of the Americans – to achieve military success without the support of coalition partners. Many of the governments that supported the Nato mission in March did so on the basis of UN Security Council resolution 1973, which authorised the use of military force to defend Libya’s civilian population and impose a ceasefire. But most of that support, particularly among the Arab states, began to disappear the moment there was a whiff that the campaign’s ultimate objective was regime change in Tripoli, rather than humanitarian assistance. The days when we might be able to finish the job ourselves are long gone. One of our senior Army officers told me at the start of the Libyan crisis that a good tank battalion could get rid of Gaddafi and his inner circle within 24 hours. But after the recent bruising experiences in Iraq and Afghanistan, there is no political will for such action, even assuming we had a tank battalion to spare. For one of the other great inconsistencies at the heart of the Libyan conflict is that it is being undertaken against a backdrop of the most savage defence cuts implemented for a generation. The Government’s insistence last year that it wanted to invest more resources in conflict prevention so that it could avoid becoming involved in unpopular military campaigns resulted in the overseas aid budget receiving a sharp increase, while the Armed Forces have been denuded of their stocks of tanks, ships and warplanes. But if David Cameron is serious about getting rid of Gaddafi, then the more military firepower we have at our disposal, the better. The strains caused by this contradiction no doubt explain why Dr Liam Fox, the Defence Secretary, has suffered the embarrassment of having yet another private letter to the Prime Minister leaked, on this occasion setting out his formal objection to give legal force to the Government’s plans to increase the aid budget by billions of pounds. But then, given our recent experiences in Iraq and Afghanistan, we should hardly be surprised by the inability of our political masters to provide an effective and joined-up strategy for delivering success in Libya. Most of what went wrong in Iraq, where a brilliantly executed military campaign to overthrow Saddam Hussein was ruined by the lack of adequate post-war planning, can be laid at the door of the last government. If, however, our military involvement in Afghanistan reaches a similarly inglorious conclusion, Mr Cameron will be as much to blame as New Labour. From its outset in 2006, Britain’s military contribution to the Nato effort has been hampered by two factors: woefully inadequate resources and our politicians’ failure to articulate a convincing mission statement. Five years later, we finally have the men and equipment in place to defeat the Taliban, not least because of General Sir David Richards’s insistence, when he became head of our Armed Forces last autumn, that Afghanistan should take precedence over Britain’s other military commitments. Whether that can remain the case now that the Government is more interested in overthrowing Gaddafi is a moot point. All Mr Cameron talks about these days is how many troops he can withdraw from Afghanistan, rather than how he expects them to achieve victory. Certainly, any reduction in Afghan force levels could make extra resources available for Libya – which may soon be necessary if, as looks increasingly likely, the conflict is heading towards stalemate. At present, most of the operational activity against Libya is being undertaken by the RAF and Royal Navy, which have mainly had a peripheral role in combat operations against the Taliban. But all that could change if, as seems likely, the Government decides to concentrate its resources on removing Gaddafi from power. Sir David has warned that Nato’s campaign needs to be expanded to include the regime’s infrastructure if the dictator is to be toppled. For example, Sir David wants Nato warplanes to bomb the perimeter fence around Gaddafi’s compound in Tripoli, a step which is not allowed under the current rules of engagement on the spurious grounds that the fence does not constitute a threat to Libya’s civilian population. But Sir David argues that if it were removed, this would demonstrate the regime’s vulnerability to ordinary Libyans, as well as affording rebels the opportunity to overthrow Gaddafi themselves. Another idea under active consideration is to cripple the dictator’s main oil refinery at Zawiyah, which supplies the regime’s energy needs. If the lights went out all over Tripoli, even Gaddafi might finally concede that his time was up. There’s still a chance we can win in Libya, but we need strong and effective leadership if we are to do so. Then, at long last, we can celebrate a rare success in a British military campaign. Con Coughlin
