Dry January will be tough – that’s why I must do it
Many of us worry about how much we drink – now we can join Allison Pearson in taking up the Alcohol Concern challenge
Grape expectations: 'The recommended units for a woman bear little relation to the amount of sauvignon blanc I merrily splosh into my glass,’ says Allison Pearson
By Allison Pearson
7:22PM GMT 29 Dec 2013
Comments
I am not an alcoholic, though alcoholism runs in my veins. My father drank steadily, and sometimes unsteadily – it was a bad sign if there was whisky before noon – and I feel the pull of alcohol like the tide feels the moon.
The other morning, at breakfast, the Small Boy and I were talking about the claim that Nigella Lawson smoked cannabis with her children, and he said: “You and me, Mum, we have to be careful about drugs because we’ve got addictive personalities.”
I felt a pang of pride, and then dismay. I hadn’t realised quite how many times in his 14 years I’d given him that particular lecture but give it I had, and enough times to make it stick. If I’m honest, and here we enter painful territory, I have always told my son to beware of drink because I see my father in him so clearly. In his brightness, in his blondness, but above all in the way he snaffles up sugary things like he’s feeding some inner sugar monster. Don’t worry, I tell myself when he’s polished off a packet of Jammie Dodgers after school, all boys like sweets and biscuits. Then I remember how my dad always had three sugars in his tea and how that sweet tooth – a craving for sweetness I have inherited – seems to be a part of the personality that drinks not for fun but out of some furious need.
So that’s why I’ve banged on about the dangers to a teenager who, thus far, has only had a few disgusted sips of fizz on special occasions, and pronounced it “sour” and “gross”.
