Given the family history with alcohol, I suppose I should be able to tell you that I heed my own warnings. But I don’t. Like many women of my age who try to combine a family with a full-time job, I drink to relax, to put me in a better mood, to make the sharp edges of a tight schedule go fuzzy. When the children were small, the debate among my fellow mums was whether you had your first glass of white wine before you bathed the kids or whether you saved it as a reward for when the little darlings were finally in bed. “Gin o’clock” for me was that moment after the kids’ tea when the kitchen looked like a battlefield, with pizza crusts and bare Barbies strewn over a wide area; and I still had the marathon of getting a squally toddler and a five-year-old into pyjamas. I would go to the fridge and pour myself a soothing glass of white wine. If I had tonic in the house, I would make a G&T, my favourite drink. There is nothing quite like the healing sting of gin for stiffening the synapses and making another viewing of Teletubbies seem bearable.
How many shattered working mothers make alcohol part of their evening routine? For me it’s not every single night, but if I haven’t had a glass of wine by 7.30pm then I definitely feel the lack. It’s as if a vital piece of punctuation were missing in the essay of the day.
Don’t get me wrong; I’m not a heavy drinker. At least I don’t regard myself as one, though I do have a sneaky sense that the recommended units for a woman’s alcohol consumption bear very little relation to the amount of sauvignon blanc I merrily splosh into a large wine glass. If a unit is one of those dismal, stumpy little glasses you get at a school parents’ evening then I must be consuming at least twice that, and even more if I give myself a top-up, which is not unusual before I settle down in front of Downton or Strictly.
By far the worst time of the week, though, is Post-Column Night. That’s Wednesday, after I’ve spent the whole day in the office at home writing my Daily Telegraph column. Trying to produce inspired, topical prose flat-out to a deadline over nine hours, during which I scarcely permit myself a visit to the loo, means that, come Gin o’clock, I am emitting a high-pitched hum of stress. Think menopausal hornet.
I can’t wait to get downstairs and have a glass of wine. Actually, arranging for it to be administered intravenously while I type would be even better. On the rare Wednesdays when I find we haven’t got any wine in the fridge, I get very agitated, angry even. “I need a drink, goddamit!”
So that’s one reason why I am glad to have signed up for Alcohol Concern’s Dry January. Not because I think it will be easy, but because I know it will be hard. The fact that it will require a serious effort of will to swerve away from the fridge every Gin o’clock tells me that my relaxing reward has become a dependency, and dependency is the mild-mannered cousin of addiction.
Besides, although I like alcohol, alcohol really doesn’t like me very much. Not any more. It seems to be another sign of middle age. Just one glass of pinot grigio and I can guarantee my sleep will be disturbed, mind slamming open like a shutter at 3am. The next morning, I feel sluggish and slow-witted. Frankly, I can no longer afford to kill brain cells voluntarily when so many are dying of their own accord.
And beneath all this, the fear. The fear that I am a drunk in waiting. All it will take is for life to deliver one grievous blow and the slippery slope becomes the north face of the Eiger, and I won’t be able to stop myself. Just as, when I go to a party and the drinks tray is brought round, I have one more than I should, then two, then three. Because whatever pause button comes as standard issue in normal people doesn’t in me.
The great actress Ellen Burstyn once described a woman who “moves from one addiction to another. All are ways for her to not feel her feelings.” I can relate to that. Any child of an alcoholic can relate to that, which is a really, really good reason not to become one yourself.
I have tried cutting back on alcohol before, with mixed success. I found if I had enough wine and gin substitutes in the house – lemon barley water, slimline tonic with ice and elderflower – then I could kid myself I wasn’t on the wagon. I’m very good at kidding myself, and overlooking my lapses. Not drinking in company will be hard. Already, I can see the pitfalls of a dry January looming – a special college dinner on the 10th, my sister’s 50th birthday on the 20th, my daughter’s 18th on the 25th. Am I really going to drink a toast in San Pellegrino?
Well, the difference this time is that I’m under observation. I want to have a month without alcohol for physical health and for mental clarity. I want to do it to show that a predisposition to alcoholism is not the same as a fixed appointment with fate. As my son said, people with addictive personalities like us have to be careful. Wish me luck.
* One of the ways to stay committed to the Dry January challenge – to go for 31 days without drinking – is to ask your friends and family to sponsor you. Set up your sponsorship online at dryjanuary.org.uk and raise money for a good cause while you’re not drinking. The money you donate will help Alcohol Concern make a real difference and help raise awareness of the problem of alcohol misuse. For full details, visit the Alcohol Concern website
