Presidential Debates
If Barack Obama and John McCain can debate, why won't Gordon Brown take on David Cameron? Dr Liam Fox, shadow secretary of state for defence, attended the debate between US Presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain, here he gives his account of the event and asks why British politics adopt a similar approach.
5:19PM BST 18 Oct 2008
It was a perfect autumn evening in New York for the third and final Presidential debate between John McCain and Barack Obama. The 700-strong audience which stood outside Hofstra University under a full moon were like a cross between a theatre audience and a sports crowd. We had just been through a scrum for tickets at a central secure location and then bussed to the hall for the debates. Security was tight – very tight. There was a tangible excitement in the air. The Obama supporters, many of them young, were heavily decorated with badges and stickers and exuded a brash (self?) confidence. The McCain supporters were more sedate and there was a feeling that their man would have to produce a bare knuckle fight to pull back up in the polls. The media swarmed around, anxious to get their vox pops ahead of the broadcast of the debate itself. Related Articles
McCain fights for political life
18 Oct 2008
We have nothing like it in Britain; it was like a cross between a party conference and election night. Eventually the doors opened and we swarmed into the cavernous hall where the air conditioning made hypothermia a distinct possibility. Then we waited. And waited. We were told not to laugh. Not to jeer. Not to applaud. Several hundred of the most enthusiastic and partisan people in America were told to remain studiously neutral. I wondered what sort of atmosphere we might expect as a result. The debate, we were told, would begin not at 9pm but 9.01 and 30 seconds precisely so that the networks could get their introductions done. Spontaneity, it seemed, was not to be the watchword of the evening. The candidates' wives took their seats in the front row and a ripple of nervous energy swept over the assembly. Then, suddenly, Senators McCain and Obama rushed on stage to a standing ovation with much whooping and cheering from their adoring fans. Engagement at last. And so it began – the jousting that would give us all a further insight into how these men would nurture the position of the world's most powerful chief executive. Yet, from the outset the structure mitigated against real momentum or fisticuffs. The debate was broken down into nine carefully-timed segments with micro-timing of each answer and counter-response rigidly enforced. I missed the freestyle encounters of the Commons and felt sorry for the constraints on the candidates whose campaign teams and lawyers had produced this debating straitjacket. John McCain began aggressively and continued in the same vein. Barack Obama remained a picture of studied calm, parrying each charge made against him. They discussed the economy, the deficit, the Vice Presidential candidates, education and energy. Each question resulted in a torrent of sound bites and counter-sound bites. Yet the resulting lack of context for each subject rendered the debate interesting but unexciting. I was surprised at how often people checked their watches. There were some flickers of real excitement such as John McCain's charge that "I'm not George Bush. If you wanted to take on George Bush you should have run four years ago," but mostly it was calm, even risk averse. The discussion of health care plans was virtually impenetrable to the outsider (and, talking to people afterwards, to many of those attending the event.) At the end, the applause for both candidates seemed strangely muted, perhaps a result of the absurd length of the campaign and the fatigue of the party troops. It had not quite produced the fireworks promised and the consensus seemed to be that while it was John McCain's best performance of the three debates, there had been no knock out blow. Yet, despite the slight sense of anticlimax I couldn't help a sense of jealousy. At least the American people had been allowed three occasions where their potential leaders had come face to face on equal terms. We are denied such an opportunity in Britain. We are told that we have Prime Minister's Questions so we need no other forum. Yet the bear pit of the House of Commons is hardly a venue for considered debate and the dynamic of Prime Ministers' Questions always favours the Prime Minister of the day. Is there any chance that next time we will be granted the courtesy given to American voters by their candidate?. Surely we should demand it? David Cameron has made clear that he is ready and up for it. Would Gordon Brown have the stomach for it? The evidence suggests not. Very recently our Prime Minister refused an invitation to engage in the gentlest of discussions with the Leader of the Opposition on the GMTV sofa. The American debate, despite its structural rigidity, had a real sense of history. This election will, after all, produce either the first African-American President or the first woman Vice President. Count yourselves lucky, voters of America. At least you get to see the goods before you buy. We in Britain are denied it by a Prime Minister who, despite all the monumental challenges we face, would rather keep us in the dark. Funny that. Presidential Debates
