St Mirren and Ross County veto plans for restructuring at Scottish Premier League meeting
Plans to restructure Scottish football look to have died after St Mirren and Ross County vetoed the proposals at a Scottish Premier League meeting. Rebel alliance: the SFL 'Gang of 10' have threatened to break away from the league to force through reform plans Photo: AFP	By Telegraph Sport, and agencies
3:07PM BST 15 Apr 2013
Follow Comments
Aberdeen chairman Stewart Milne emerged from talks to announce the teams had failed to secure the 11-1 majority needed to send the plans to the Scottish Football League. The proposals would have seen both league bodies merge in a 12-12-18 structure with a pyramid system below. The most controversial aspect was for the top two leagues to split into three after 22 games in a bid to generate extra revenue. St Mirren last week confirmed they were going to vote against the deal, which had been agreed in principle in January. Their chairman Stewart Gilmour refused to comment after the talks at Hampden, but Milne said: "One club in particular you would need to ask just exactly what their agenda is - St Mirren. Related Articles
