Dr Sarah Wollaston MP: 'Fat and happy? Forget it. That's why I'm subjecting myself to RideLondon'
For Tory MP Dr Sarah Wollaston, it's time to work off the mince pies and start training for RideLondon, a gruelling 100 mile bike race this August. Can weight loss really be so much harder in your fifties? The real deadly white powder in most of our lives is sugar, says Dr Sarah Wollaston MP Photo: JAY WILLIAMS By Dr Sarah Wollaston MP
3:42PM GMT 02 Jan 2014
Is it really so much harder to lose weight in your fifties? Many women used to tell me so and now the supersize chickens have come home to roost. Did my 'metabolism' suddenly change once I hit my half-century or was it more that I stopped running and started grazing? Once past a certain point the reality is that it is extraordinarily difficult to return to a 'normal' weight. Fat and happy? Forget it. Obesity is more likely to be associated with a downward spiral of low self-esteem, stress and fatigue, aggravated by junk food and drink. The real deadly white powder in most of our lives is sugar. Many women also struggle with secret drinking, especially if that becomes their anaesthetic of choice for a failing relationship, financial problems or an empty nest. Comfort and binge eating followed by crash dieting rarely leads to any improvement in body image or mood. Like any other addiction, change probably starts with some honesty; that there is more to middle age obesity than 'metabolism'. It really is all about the calories. Related Articles
