It's never too late to turn it around but there are no safe short cuts; you can only lose weight if you take in less than your body uses. The calories burned through exercise are surprising low and it is not possible to exercise yourself thin; you have to reduce calorie intake too. That said, exercise really matters as it improves well-being and motivation, controlling the drive to binge. Fitness independently also reduces some of the risks from the host of medical problems which obesity brings in its wake. So why is it so difficult to just get on and do it? Too little time, too painful, too embarrassing, didn't work last time ... The trouble with overly ambitious New Year's resolutions is that they can just set you up to fail. The draft NICE guidance on obesity, expected to be published in May this year, talks of the need to make gradual changes to eating habits and physical activity, as too many changes at once can lead to an increased risk of failure. If your goal is to improve your health, even small changes in weight make a significant difference. But the advice needs to be tailored to individuals and gradual change won't suit everyone. Some people do need more of a push, like a realistic but achievable physical challenge to get them to train. I know that I do. That's why I'm taking part in RideLondon this August – as this pic shows, I've started training already for the 100 mile race on a tandem with a Middle-Aged Man in Lycra (MAMIL). Whatever the route to shifting excess weight, a positive non-blame approach is essential but honesty about intake and some of the other causes is not the same as blame. My tips for successful dieting Don't drink your calories: It's worth checking out how many calories are hidden in a large glass of wine, fruit juice or latte. Some seemingly healthy juices can pack up to 600 calories a bottle. Eat off a smaller plate and cut right down on bread and pasta. Most of all, if you are addicted to junk, have absolutely nothing in your shopping trolley or at home in your cupboards to lead you astray. Zero-tolerance approach: Like any other addiction, when you cut out sugar and alcohol expect the first week to be miserable. It doesn't have to be hell though; you can reduce the lows and improve motivation by joining a group or finding a no-nonsense training buddy. Issue yourself an ultimatum: As for my training buddy, the front of my tandem has issued an ultimatum; lose a stone or RideLondon on my own bike (all by myself). One hundred miles in August is a long way without a MAMIL; probably more painful than that long overdue change in lifestyle. Time to ditch the excuses and the calories, ramp up the exercise and see if the advice works. As for government, it's time to take the obesity epidemic far more seriously and look again at the devastating human cost of junk food and drink and of ultra-cheap alcohol. It is time for a price differential between high sugar versus low calorie alternatives and, if we want to help reverse the super sizing of Britain, to put an end to the super sizing of junk food and drink. Dr Sarah Wollaston, 51, is the Conservative MP for Totnes. She has started a training blog ahead of RideLondon in August, which records her favourite cycling routes around Devon and encourages others to add their own
